# Web26 Repository Guardrails

## Purpose

This repository is a portfolio-quality full-stack implementation for `pedroportella.com`.

Keep changes professional, scoped and consistent with the existing architecture.

## Repository Boundaries

- Keep frontend code under `frontend`.
- Keep the public Next.js app under `frontend/apps/web`.
- Keep shared frontend packages under `frontend/packages`.
- Keep Drupal backend code, config and migration code under `backend`.
- Keep Docker support files under `docker`.
- Keep public handover and technical documentation under `docs`.

Do not move code across these boundaries without a clear architecture reason.

## Public Documentation

Public documentation must read as handover and technical decision material.

Do not describe work as stages, batches, implementation diaries or private planning notes.

Do not reference private working notes, internal AI notes or migration diary files.

## Frontend Architecture

- Keep content access in `frontend/packages/services-content`.
- Keep design tokens in `frontend/packages/ui-tokens`.
- Keep static reusable assets in `frontend/packages/ui-assets`.
- Keep shared React components in `frontend/packages/ui-library`.
- Keep pure helpers in `frontend/packages/utils`.
- Keep app-specific routing and page composition in `frontend/apps/web`.

Avoid mixing API/domain logic into UI packages.

## Backend Architecture

- Keep Drupal exported config under `backend/config/sync`.
- Keep custom Drupal modules under `backend/modules/custom`.
- Keep migration definitions and process plugins inside `backend/modules/custom/web26_migration`.
- Preserve legacy IDs used for reconciliation.
- Treat migration imports as repeatable and rollback-friendly.

## Docker Runtime

- Keep CMS runtime changes in `docker-compose.yml` and `docker`.
- Keep environment values documented through `.env.example`.
- Do not commit generated database volumes, public files or private files.

## Change Discipline

- Prefer small, focused changes that preserve existing package boundaries.
- Validate YAML/PHP/TypeScript changes with the nearest available command.
- Do not introduce unrelated refactors while completing a migration or feature step.
- Keep public-facing text concise, credible and portfolio-ready.

## Delivery Notes

When summarising work, include:

- what changed;
- what was validated;
- any known limitation or next step;
- a suggested git commit message.

## Commit Message Convention

Always suggest a commit message after implementation work.

Use:

```txt
type(scope): past-tense-verb summary
```

Friendly regex for future checks:

```regex
^(feat|fix|refactor|chore|perf|ci|ops|build|docs|style|revert|test)\([a-z0-9]+(?:-[a-z0-9]+)*\): [a-z]+ed\b[a-z0-9 ,.'/-]*$
```

The summary must start with a past-tense verb, such as `added`, `documented`, `developed`, `implemented`, `reverted`, `refactored`, `changed`, `improved` or `resolved`.

Allowed types:

- `feat`: adds a new feature.
- `fix`: fixes a bug.
- `refactor`: restructures code without adding a feature or fixing a bug.
- `chore`: miscellaneous maintenance that does not modify source or test behavior.
- `perf`: improves performance.
- `ci`: changes continuous integration.
- `ops`: affects infrastructure, deployment, backup or recovery.
- `build`: affects the build system, dependencies or project versioning.
- `docs`: changes documentation.
- `style`: changes formatting without changing code meaning.
- `revert`: reverts a previous commit.
- `test`: adds or corrects tests.

Examples:

```txt
docs(web26): documented backend migration runtime guardrails
feat(migration): added Drupal source runtime verification
chore(repo): added Cursor repository guardrails
feat(fe): implemented new button style
feat(be): improved api resilience
fix(fe): resolved paragraph overflow on mobile viewport
```
